- Find P(max(X₁, X₂, X₃) > 8) = P(max(X₁, X₂, X₃) ≥ 9)

**Solution:**

P(max ≥ 9) = P(at least one drug has ≥ 9 successes)

Using inclusion-exclusion:
P(max ≥ 9) = P(X₁ ≥ 9 or X₂ ≥ 9 or X₃ ≥ 9)

First, find P(Xᵢ ≥ 9) for a single drug:
P(X ≥ 9) = P(X = 9) + P(X = 10)

For Binomial(10, 0.7):
- P(X = 9) = C(10,9) × (0.7)⁹ × (0.3)¹ = 10 × 0.040353607 × 0.3 = 0.121060821
- P(X = 10) = C(10,10) × (0.7)¹⁰ × (0.3)⁰ = 1 × 0.0282475249 × 1 = 0.0282475249

P(X ≥ 9) = 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459

By inclusion-exclusion (assuming independence):
P(X₁ ≥ 9 or X₂ ≥ 9 or X₃ ≥ 9) = 3P(X ≥ 9) - 3P(X ≥ 9)² + P(X ≥ 9)³

Let p = P(X ≥ 9) = 0.1493083459

P(max ≥ 9) = 3p - 3p² + p³
= 3(0.1493083459) - 3(0.1493083459)² + (0.1493083459)³
= 0.4479250377 - 3(0.0222930595) + 0.0033277456
= 0.4479250377 - 0.0668791785 + 0.0033277456
= 0.3843736048

Rounding to reasonable significant figures (4-5):

